    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Too Easy on Emissions</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Richard Wolfson, professor of physics and environmental studies at Middlebury College, welcomes Gov George E Pataki's decision to impose tougher auto emissions standards in New York, but says reduction in carbon dioxide emissions will only be achieved by burning less fuel (Nov 7 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Gov. George E. Pataki's decision to impose tougher auto emissions standards is welcome news (front page, Nov. 7). But the public needs to understand that neither new state standards nor existing federal emissions regulations cover the dominant emission from fossil-fueled motor vehicles -- carbon dioxide, the leading cause of global climate change.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Gov. George E. Pataki's decision to impose tougher auto emissions standards is welcome news (front page, Nov. 7). But the public needs to understand that neither new state standards nor existing federal emissions regulations cover the dominant emission from fossil-fueled motor vehicles -- carbon dioxide, the leading cause of global climate change.</p>
        <p>Only by burning less fuel will we reduce carbon dioxide emissions. Unfortunately, mandating higher fuel economy for vehicles has become a political impossibility in today's Congress. Meanwhile, the auto industry and consumers continue to drive the country's average fuel mileage down and carbon dioxide emissions up as they produce and embrace ever larger, less efficient vehicles like sport utilities.</p>
        <p>RICHARD WOLFSON  Weybridge, Vt., Nov. 7, 1999</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of physics and environmental studies at Middlebury College.</p>
      </block>
